Consistent with two recent reports [1,12], lymphopenia was common and, in some cases, severe. However, based on a larger sample size and cases recruited throughout China, we found a markedly lower case fatality rate (1.4%) as compared with that reportedly recently [1,12]. The fatality rate was lower (0.88%) when incorporating additional pilot data from Guangdong province (N=603) where effective prevention has been undertaken (unpublished data). Our findings were consistent with the national official statistics, reporting the mortality of 2.01% in China out of 28,018 cases as of February 6th, 2020 [11,23]. Early isolation, early diagnosis and early management might have collectively contributed to the marked reduction in mortality in Guangdong. The documents were collected by the Cabinet Secretariat between April 2017 and March 2019. Of the 23 documents, 13 are classified dispatches from Japanese consulates in China to the Foreign Ministry in Tokyo dated 1938, the year after the Marco Polo Bridge Incident that sparked the Second Sino-Japanese War. One dispatch from the consul general of Jinan to the foreign minister reports that the Japanese invasion had caused a surge in prostitution in the area, with a head count of 101 geisha from mainland Japan, 110 comfort women from mainland Japan, and 228 comfort women from the Korean Peninsula, which had been annexed in 1910. The dispatch says that as Japanese forces had made further advances, ‚Äúat least 500 comfort women must be concentrated here by the end of April.‚Äù It also notes that 186 women had ridden south in military vehicles after the occupation of Xuzhou in Jiangsu province. The documents lend weight to the landmark 1993 apology statement by then-Chief Cabinet Secretary Yohei Kono that accepted blame for the Japanese military‚Äôs involvement in recruiting comfort women, in many cases against their own will, and apologized to them.Hirofumi Hayashi, a professor at Kanto Gakuin University, said the documents proved that ‚Äúthe military had an active hand in gathering women.‚Äù‚ÄúThey were sounding out the Foreign Ministry through the consulates,‚Äù he said. The exact number of comfort women remains unknown, with estimates ranging from 20,000 to hundreds of thousands. The women were recruited from mainland Japan, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan and other countries. The issue continues to be a source of friction between Japan and South Korea. But evil PM Shinjo Abe continues to deny existence of such."}]}

You didn\'t ask to be thrown into this world," he said, describing depression as a grim game.\nHe is just one of an increasing number of young people who are suffering from depression and are reaching out for help.\nLink in bio @straits_times\nüì∏: MARK CHEONG\n#mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #youarenotalone', 'mentions': ['straits_times'], 'hashtags': ['mentalhealth', 'mentalhealthawareness', 'youarenotalone']}, {'author': 'ryan.jeanwei', 'comment': 'I can relate to checking taps and Electric switches.'}, {'author': 'vanitha_vasudevan', 'comment': 'I admire your fighting spirit brother!'}, {'author': 'altuzacademydyslexiamalaysia', 'comment': 'üôÇ'}, {'author': 'floradise.studio', 'comment': 'Sending hugs and love üåπ'}, {'author': 'rafael_wee', 'comment': 'The art is beautiful'}, {'author': 'pammyrose6', 'comment': 'üëçüôèüí™üèªüôè'}, {'author': 'durum_doner_official', 'comment': 'Salmon mentaiko disorder'}, {'author': 'manuscript12345', 'comment': 'It is courageous of him to come forth with his story.'}, {'author': 'kindnesssg', 'comment': 'Be kind to yourself and those around you, be greater. #BeGreaterSG', 'hashtags': ['BeGreaterSG']}]}

His great-grandfather, the late Sultan Ibrahim, opened the Causeway in 1923.\nBefore the Causeway was built, passengers had to disembark and take a ferry across the Johor Strait. The land link meant that people from both sides of the Strait could finally trundle across the narrow sea that divided Singapore and West Malaysia in a train or car.\nThe railway station at Tanjong Pagar was completed in 1932. Built near the port, it was envisioned as the southernmost node of a circuitry of rail lines potentially spanning to Siberia.\nThat vision did not come to pass as cars became faster and air travel overtook rail transport. After World War II, they were replaced by trishaws.\nThe trolley buses, which ran on electricity, were the first public buses on Singapore roads. They were owned by the Singapore Traction Company (STC), and started running in 1929.\nMotor buses began operating in the 1930s and the trolley bus system ended in 1962. There were about a dozen bus companies in addition to the STC from the 1930s to the 1960s.\nAfter a number of mergers, Singapore Bus Services, or what we now know as SBS Transit, was formed in 1973.\nThe Jinrikisha Station, built in 1903, was bought by Hong Kong action star Jackie Chan in 2007. It now houses karaoke bars, a restaurant and offices.\nTEXT BY CHEW HUI MIN / PHOTOS: FILE, DESMOND WEE\n// üì∑ For more Then & Now photos, go to our bio, or here: http://str.sg/4bLG\n#thestraitstimes #thenandnow #oldphotos #oldsingapore #tanjongpagar #trolleybus #rickshaw #bus #singapore', 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'thenandnow', 'oldphotos', 'oldsingapore', 'tanjongpagar', 'trolleybus', 'rickshaw', 'bus', 'singapore']}, {'author': 'j_banding', 'comment': 'Omg! The river, which was crammed with lighters and tongkang, was described as reeking of ‚Äúpungent hydrogen sulphide and methane from rotting wastes and raw sewage discharged into the water‚Äù.\nBefore the clean-up, the sources of pollution had to be removed or re-sited. These included pig farms, duck farms, street hawkers, hanging latrines and more. The whole process, from 1977 when former Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew issued the challenge to clean up the Singapore River and Kallang Basin, took 10 years.\nIn the 1983 photo, the many vessels plying the river were a thing of the recent past, and the wooden poles that the boats used as mooring points still pierced the riverbed.\nOn the left bank, are the wooden houses and zinc roofs of Kampung Bugis. In 1986, dozens of boat repair yards had moved from Kallang to Tuas and Jurong. By 1987, the Kallang Basin mud banks were dredged, and sandy beaches were created.\nNow, waterfront condominiums are being built where once kampung houses stood, and the area is set to become a residential and lifestyle district.\nBut the area has always been a ‚Äúresidential district‚Äù, having been occupied since the 18th century by Orang Biduanda Kallang, an indigenous fishing community.\nTo the right, is the unmistakable outline of the old National Stadium, now replaced by the Sports Hub. The old National Stadium, the birthplace of the ‚ÄúKallang Roar‚Äù, was opened in 1973 and closed in 2008.\nThe $1.33-billion Singapore Sports Hub, which opened in 2014, has a 55,000-capacity stadium with a retractable roof, as well as an indoor aquatics arena.\nTEXT BY CHEW HUIMIN / PHOTOS: AZIZ HUSSIN, LIM YAOHUI\n// üì∑ For more Then & Now photos, go to our bio, or here: http://str.sg/4bLG\n#thestraitstimes #thenandnow #oldphotos #oldsingapore #kallang #kallangriver #kallangwave #nationalstadium', 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'thenandnow', 'oldphotos', 'oldsingapore', 'kallang', 'kallangriver', 'kallangwave', 'nationalstadium']}, {'author': 'jamesshaohong', 'comment': '$1.33 billion sports hub the greatest joke'}, {'author': 'saffron.31', 'comment': 'Thk you Sir LKY.'}, {'author': 'jesssayang', 'comment': 'I love old picture ‚ù§Ô∏è'}]}

Jackson in 1822. Over the years, the road grew in length, and the area developed. It now extends from Crawford Street to Elgin Bridge. Beyond the bridge is South Bridge Road.\nBut the history in that area could extend before Sir Stamford Raffles' landing. In 1994, 14th century coins and pottery were found at the junction of North Bridge Road and High Street, indicating that Singapore was an active trading post 400 years before the British came ashore.\nHistoric buildings along the road include the Raffles Hotel, The Capitol and Chijmes, which was once the site of a church and the Convent of the Holy Infant Jesus.\nRaffles Institution also had its campus here, from the 1800s to 1972.\nTEXT BY CHEW HUIMIN / ST PHOTOS: FILE, LIM YAOHUI // üì∑ For more Then & Now photos, go to our bio, or here: http://str.sg/4bLG\n#thestraitstimes #thenandnow #oldphotos #oldsingapore #singapore #northbridgeroad #modernisation", 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'thenandnow', 'oldphotos', 'oldsingapore', 'singapore', 'northbridgeroad', 'modernisation']}, {'author': 'elizabeth.wong.963', 'comment': 'Brings back such fond memories of Liang Seah Street and the neighbouring streets.'}, {'author': 'derikpoh', 'comment': 'nice... no ERP gantries'}, {'author': 'tanchunleejoash', 'comment': 'Very good'}, {'author': 'khoojiazhenmiki', 'comment': 'The district I grew up in - love the bustling streets 24/7. It was renamed Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park in 2012.\n\nBishan Park, completed in 1988, is one of the biggest parks in Singapore. When first constructed, it featured ponds, a lake, a football field, a frangipani garden and a ‚Äúfloating amphitheatre‚Äù among other features within its 42ha of greenery.\n\nThe park was a hit with residents, and many people walked, jogged, cycled, dated and fed the fish in the pond there. People could even rent paddle boats and fish at the ponds in the 1990s.\n\nTragically, a nine-year-old girl fell into one of the ponds in the park and drowned in 1991, and although concerns about safety were expressed then, no other accidents have been reported.\n\nIt is called Bishan Park but the verdant corridor sits between two HDB towns - Bishan and Ang Mo Kio - and was meant to be a buffer zone between the two. The park was renamed Bishan-Ang Mo Kio Park in 2012 after a major revamp under the Active Beautiful Clean (ABC) Waters programme.\n\nConcrete water bodies and canals within the park were transformed into a 3km river by scientists using soil bio-engineering techniques for the first time in Singapore. The huge canal that used to separate residents from the park is now a meandering river, with flood plains.\n\nThis new ‚Äúnatural look‚Äù comes with a high-tech safety system that employs water level sensors, lights, sirens and audio announcements to alert people at the park when heavy rain or rising water levels are expected.\n\nNow it appears that it is not only people who enjoy the park: The most recent fans of the new waterways are a family of otters who have made the park their new haunt.\n\nTEXT BY CHEW HUI MIN / PHOTOS: FILE, DESMOND FOO // üì∑For more Then & Now photos, go to: http://str.sg/4bLG\n\n#thestraitstimes #thenandnow #oldphotos #oldsingapore #singapore #sgig #igsg #bishan #bishanpark #parks', 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'thenandnow', 'oldphotos', 'oldsingapore', 'singapore', 'sgig', 'igsg', 'bishan', 'bishanpark', 'parks']}, {'author': 'craigrobertmartin', 'comment': "It's a wonderful park"}, {'author': 'philip_yong2', 'comment': "It's a wonderful park"}, {'author': 'lazeemin846', 'comment': "It's a wonderful park"}, {'author': 'anxietywarrior7582', 'comment': '@hanaradaisirkhri', 'mentions': ['hanaradaisirkhri']}, {'author': 'hanaradaisirkhri', 'comment': 'Remember we went cycling with our late grandpa Abdul Hamid whenever we came over to his place, fond memories ‚ù§ @akuisteridia7582', 'mentions': ['akuisteridia7582']}]}

It is here that Singapore's Thieves' Market reportedly started in the 1930s, where people could buy back their belongings from thieves selling pilfered items at makeshift stalls. This second-hand market became a fascinating place to shop for many people, including tourists.\nThe market survived through World War II and attempts to close the area down in 1982 and 1994.\nIt will close for good on July 10, 2017.\nFor more old photos of Sungei Road market, link in bio or here:\nhttp://str.sg/4aLr\nST PHOTOS: LIM YAOHUI, NIVASH JOYVIN, SIMON KER, HAIRIS\n#thestraitstimes #sungeiroad #sungeiroadthievesmarket #thievesmarket #singapore #oldsingapore #oldphotos #thenandnow", 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'sungeiroad', 'sungeiroadthievesmarket', 'thievesmarket', 'singapore', 'oldsingapore', 'oldphotos', 'thenandnow']}, {'author': 'limyihong88', 'comment': 'Gone. They are mainly of the Teochew style of shophouses.\nFrom 1977 to 1987, the heavily polluted Singapore River was cleaned up, and the bumboats and wooden boats called tongkangs that plied the river became a thing of the past.\nClarke Quay was designated a heritage conservation area in 1989, and it reopened in 1993 as a family-friendly attraction with more than 170 retail shops, 17 food and beverage joints and a $25-million adventure ride.\nHowever, the project proved commercially unviable and Clarke Quay was redeveloped as a dining and nightlife destination in the early 2000s. The changes and the opening of the Clarke Quay MRT station in 2003 increased visitor traffic.\nTEXT BY CHEW HUI MIN / ST PHOTOS: FILE, LIM SIN THAI // üì∑For more Then & Now photos, go to: http://str.sg/4bLG\n#thestraitstimes #sgig #igsg #thenandnow #oldsingapore #oldphotos #clarkequay #clarkequaysg #singaporeriver #singapore', 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'sgig', 'igsg', 'thenandnow', 'oldsingapore', 'oldphotos', 'clarkequay', 'clarkequaysg', 'singaporeriver', 'singapore']}, {'author': 'jobandshop', 'comment': 'Nice üòä'}, {'author': 'meernasirudeen', 'comment': 'Wonderful üåû'}, {'author': 'thankful57', 'comment': 'My house is half in the picture besides the Chinese temple My neighbours usually go to the temple to collect praying candles which was slightly used to light up the toilets in the night'}]}

{'key': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BVrNcQgFMTa/', 'img_urls': ['https://instagram.fsin7-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/19379845_1563855750314802_552151353372180480_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsin7-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=106&_nc_ohc=DWHFnujpng8AX9_VjwM&oh=3edeaed361fe2cde24390877f024f2b3&oe=5E98EF75', 'https://instagram.fsin7-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t51.2885-15/e35/19367436_1573017256055694_835369661603250176_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fsin7-1.fna.fbcdn.net&_nc_cat=106&_nc_ohc=terYr1GHjtwAX9TuItt&oh=836c164f44db0f66eb14e30d467c0787&oe=5E991B93'], 'location': 'Geylang Serai Market', 'datetime': '2017-06-23T08:20:19.000Z', 'likes': 807, 'comments': [{'author': 'straits_times', 'comment': 'Geylang Serai in 1970, and in June last year, with a Hari Raya bazaar at the site of the former Malay Village.\nIs Geylang named after factories or a fierce orang laut tribe? The name is believed to be a corruption of either the Malay word ‚Äúkilang‚Äù, which means factory, or the name of a tribe that lived, and pirated, along the coast and rivers of Singapore - the orang gallang.\n\nAs for the factories, they were operated by the Alsagoffs, a wealthy Arab family who owned a 1,000-acre property in the area.\n\nGeylang Serai was originally known as Geylang Kelapa (which means ‚Äúcoconut‚Äù in Malay), due to the large number of coconut trees planted there in the 1840s and 1850s.\n\nLater, the Alsagoffs started a plantation for serai or lemongrass, and produced aromatic oil which was in demand in Europe. As demand for the oil fell around 1890, the Alsagoff plantation cultivated other crops, but the name Geylang Serai stuck.\n\nGeylang Serai is one of the oldest Malay Settlements in Singapore, and an important marketplace, social and cultural centre for the Malay community. It was designated a historic area in 2000.\n\nWhile the villages were cleared in the 1960s and 1970s, it retains its ‚ÄúMalayness‚Äù, and the annual bazaar during the fasting month of Ramadan draws huge crowds.\n\nThe area where part of the bazaar is sited now used to be the Geylang Serai Malay Village.\nüì∑For more Then & Now photos, go to: http://str.sg/4bLG\nST PHOTOS: JUNID JUANI, LIM YAOHUI\n#thestraitstimes #singapore #oldsingapore #oldphotos #throwbackfriday #throwback #geylang #geylangserai #geylangbazaar #hariraya #harirayapuasa', 'hashtags': ['thestraitstimes', 'singapore', 'oldsingapore', 'oldphotos', 'throwbackfriday', 'throwback', 'geylang', 'geylangserai', 'geylangbazaar', 'hariraya', 'harirayapuasa']}, {'author': 'foodie_tl', 'comment': 'Nice old photo'}, {'author': 'love_to_swim64', 'comment': 'So quiet and peaceful then'}, {'author': 'redstilton', 'comment': 'nice'}, {'author': 'tmesquitafox', 'comment': 'straits_times - The, Curtidas de gra√ßa no www.igseguidores .com (23/06 21:42) #nMo9o3fJ5P', 'hashtags': ['nMo9o3fJ5P']}, {'author': 'superaprons', 'comment': 'Like it!'}, {'author': 'nornizarsharon', 'comment': 'Kelab Arab'}]}

Within each large kamakura is a snow altar dedicated to the water gods , to whom people pray for plenty of clear water . A charcoal brazier is set up to provide warmth and grill rice cakes. In the evenings, festival visitors are invited into the kamakura and offered rice cakes and amazake, a type of sweet rice wine. In return, the visitors make an offering at the altar.\nThe Yokote Kamakura Festival has a history dating back about 450 years, and was traditionally held to offer hospitality to deities who supposedly came from far way.\nThe festival is typically held on Feb 15 and 16, after the Chinese New Year. Having few predators on the island, the Albino Wallabies have maintained healthy numbers, yet are one of the rarest fauna found on the island.
